vectorData.altText: 6. A dermatome is formed by contributions from both the dorsal ramus and the ventral ramus that arise from a given spinal nerve.
That's right!  The dorsal ramus innervates the para-axial portions of the dermatome and the ventral ramus innervates the remainder of the dermatome.

A myotome      is the group of muscle cells controlled by the somatic motor fibres contained within a single spinal nerve, and therefore arising from a single spinal level. 
This means that each movement is controlled by one, or perhaps two spinal levels. This is of great clinical significance; weakness of a specific movement can help a clinician to localize a lesion to a specific spinal nerve or level.

A dermatome      is the area of skin supplied with cutaneous sensory fibres originating from a single spinal nerve, and therefore arising from a single spinal level. Cutaneous sensory fibres are distributed to the dermatome by both the dorsal and ventral rami. In general, there is a dermatome that corresponds to every spinal nerve / segment, except C1.
This means that a sensory deficit in a specific region of skin can help a clinician to localize a lesion to  a specific spinal level or nerve     .
At this point, you are expected to understand this concept. You will be required to learn the details of dermatomes in CPC-3.
